{{Sortname|Ilaria|Ercolani|nolink=yes}} \n| {{Sortname|Veronica|Conti|nolink=yes}}   \n| {{Sortname|Lo|Strego|nolink=yes}} \n| {{Sortname|Claudio|Podeschi|nolink=yes}}  \n|{{center|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018/second-semi-final/results/san-marino|title=Results of the Second Semi-Final of Lisbon 2018|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| {{center|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]]}} \n| {{Sortname|Paolo|Rondelli}} \n| {{Sortname|Danilo|Berardi|nolink=yes}} \n| {{Sortname|Sabrina|Minguzzi|nolink=yes}}  \n| {{Sortname|Elia|Gasperoni|nolink=yes}} \n| {{Sortname|Marilia|Reffi|nolink=yes}}\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/tel-aviv-2019/first-semi-final/results/san-marino|title=Results of the First Semi-Final of Tel Aviv 2019|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commentators and spokespersons===\nFor the show's broadcast on SMRTV, various commentators have been hired throughout the years to provide comment on the Concert in the local language. At Eurovision, after all points are calculated, the presenters of the show call upon each voting country to invite their respective spokesperson to announce the results of their vote on-screen. In 2014, San Marino RTV also provided an English commentary in its internet streaming, with John Kennedy O'Connor and Jamarie Milkovic directly from Copenhagen.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Year(s)\n! Commentator(s)\n! Spokesperson(s)\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n|Lia Fiorio, Gigi Restivo ||Roberto Moretti \n|<ref name=spokes>{{cite news|url=https://www.eurofestivalnews.com/2013/03/27/sm-tv-san-marino-confermati-i-conduttori-per-leurovision-2013/|title=SM TV San Marino: confermati i conduttori per l\u2019Eurovision 2013|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=28 March 2013|work=eurofestivalnews.com|language=Italian|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|date=24 May 2008|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2008|location=[[Belgrade]], Serbia}}</ref>\n|- \n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\u2013{{Escyr|2010}}\n|{{n/a|No broadcast}} ||{{n/a|Did not participate}} ||{{n/a|N/A}}\n|- \n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Lia Fiorio, Gigi Restivo ||[[Nicola Della Valle]]\n|<ref name=spokes/><ref>{{cite AV media|date=14 May 2011|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2011|location=[[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Germany}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n|Monica Fabbri\n|<ref name=spokes/><ref>{{cite AV media|date=26 May 2012|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2012|location=[[Baku]], Azerbaijan}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\n|[[John Kennedy O'Connor]] \n|<ref name=2013commentatorjury/><ref>{{cite web|last=Roxburgh|first=Gordon|title=\"Good evening Malm\u00f6\" - Jury order revealed|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/good-evening-malmoe-voting-order-revealed|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=18 May 2013|date=18 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|date=18 May 2013|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2013|location=[[Malm\u00f6]], Sweden}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}\n|Lia Fiorio, Gigi Restivo, John Kennedy O'Connor, Jamarie Milkovic ||[[Michele Perniola]]\n|<ref>{{cite AV media|date=10 May 2014|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2014|location=[[Copenhagen]], Denmark}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2015}}\n|rowspan=\"2\" |Lia Fiorio, Gigi Restivo, John Kennedy O'Connor ||[[Valentina Monetta]]\n|<ref name=\"spokesperson\">{{cite AV media|date=23 May 2015|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2015|location=[[Vienna]], Austria}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n|[[:it:Irol |Irol MC]] \n|<ref>{{cite AV media|date=14 May 2016|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2016|location=[[Stockholm]], Sweden}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2017}}\n|rowspan=\"3\" |Lia Fiorio, Gigi Restivo ||Lia Fiorio\n|<ref>{{cite AV media|date=13 May 2017|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2017|location=[[Kiev]], Ukraine}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018}}\n|John Kennedy O'Connor \n|<ref>{{cite AV media|date=12 May 2018|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2018|location=[[Lisbon]], Portugal}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n|Monica Fabbri\n|<ref>{{cite AV media|date=18 May 2019|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2019|location=[[Tel Aviv]], Israel}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:ESC 2008 - San Marino - Miodio, 1st semifinal.jpg|[[Miodio]] in Belgrade ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]])\nFile:ESC2013 - San Marino 03 (crop).jpg|[[Valentina Monetta]] in Malm\u00f6 ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]])\nFile:ESC2014 - San Marino 01.jpg|[[Valentina Monetta]] in Copenhagen ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]])\nFile:20150516 ESC 2015 Michele Perniola & Anita Simoncini 8632.jpg|[[Michele Perniola]] & [[Anita Simoncini]] in Vienna ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]])\nFile:ESC2016 - San Marino 09.jpg|[[Serhat (singer)|Serhat]] in Stockholm ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]])\nFile:Eurovision Song Contest 2017, Semi Final 2 Rehearsals. Photo 228.jpg|[[Valentina Monetta]] & [[Jimmie Wilson (singer)|Jimmie Wilson]] in Kyiv ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]])\nFile:ESC2018 - San Marino 05.jpg|[[Jessika Muscat|Jessika]] and [[Jenifer Brening]] in Lisbon ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]])\nFile:San Marino Eurovision 2019.jpg|[[Serhat (singer)|Serhat]] in Tel Aviv ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]])\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[San Marino in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{San Marino in Eurovision}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest|San Marino]]\n[[Category:San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|none}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox song contest country\n| Name = San Marino\n| Member station = [[San Marino RTV|SMRTV]]\n| National selection event = \n{{Collapsible list\n | title = Internal selection\n | 2008\n | 2011\u20132017\n | 2019\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title = National final\n | '''''1 in 360'''''\n | 2018\n\n}}\n| ESC apps = 10 (2 finals)\n| ESC first = {{Escyr|2008}}\n| ESC last =\n| ESC best = 19th: {{Escyr|2019}}\n| ESC worst = Last {{small|SF}}: {{Escyr|2008}}, {{Escyr|2017}}\n| Website = \n| EBU page = https://eurovision.tv/country/san-marino\n| Current = 2019\n}}\n\n[[San Marino]] has participated in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] 10 times, debuting in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008 contest]], followed by participation from [[Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]] onward. Having failed to qualify in their first four attempts, San Marino qualified for the Eurovision final for the first time in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]]. [[Valentina Monetta]] represented [[San Marino]] in 2012, 2013 and 2014, making her the first Sanmarinese singer to participate in three consecutive contests. Her most recent representation in 2017 together with [[Jimmie Wilson (singer)|Jimmie Wilson]], gave her the title of the woman with the most participations ever in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. In {{escyr|2019}}, [[Serhat (singer)|Serhat]] managed to qualify, marking the second appearance of the country in a Eurovision final.\n\n==History==\nIn June 2007, [[San Marino RTV|Radiotelevisione della Repubblica di San Marino]] (SMRTV), the [[San Marino|Sammarinese]] public service broadcaster, indicated interest in joining the contest in the near future, all depending on the interest of the stockholders, especially [[Italy|Italian]] broadcaster [[RAI]], which had been absent from the Contest since [[Eurovision Song Contest 1997|1997]]. Five months later, the broadcaster confirmed its participation in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/9694/exclusive_san_marino_in_belgrade_confirmed/|title=Exclusive: San Marino in Belgrade confirmed|publisher=ESCToday|date=2007-11-21|accessdate=2007-11-21|last=Hondal|first=V\u00edctor}}</ref> The first Sammarinese entry in the Eurovision Song Contest was [[Miodio]], with the [[Italian language]] song \"[[Complice]]\". San Marino holds the honour of being the 50th country to participate at Eurovision, participating 5th in the first semi-final of the contest. Miodio failed to qualify for the final, receiving just 5 points in total and coming last. SMRTV had originally planned to compete at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009 contest]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]], with the Sammarinese Minister of Culture announcing shortly after the 2008 contest that they had \"good hopes to return\". SMRTV announced that it would be reviewing the 2008 contest, and would have a decision on 2009 participation by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/12078/san_marino__we_have_good_hopes_to_return/|title=San Marino: \"We have good hopes to return\"|last=Floras|first=Stella|date=2008-06-10|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=3608|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103113241/http://oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=3608|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-01-03|title=San Marino: State television hopes to participate in 2009 as well|date=2008-06-10|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref> It was then rumoured that the country would not be participating in the 2009 contest following reports that SMRTV would withdraw due to poor results at the 2008 contest,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=4439|title=San Marino & Monaco out?|last=Konstantopoulos|first=Fotis|date=2008-11-27|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref> however SMRTV rebuked the claim and confirmed its interest in the 2009 contest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/12654/san_marino_not_quitting_after_poor_start/|title=San Marino not quitting after poor start|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=2008-12-08|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref> In the end, SMRTV announced that it would not participate in the 2009 contest, having already applied to enter. The broadcaster insisted that this was not due to the poor results of the previous year, but financial difficulties faced by SMRTV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/12736/san_marino_leaves_eurovision_song_contest/|title=San Marino leaves Eurovision Song Contest|last=Viniker|first=Barry|date=2008-12-18|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=2008-12-18}}</ref> San Marino did not return for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2010]], again stating financial reasons preventing participation.<ref>{{cite web|last=Floras|first=Stella|title=No San Marino either for Eurovision 2010|url=http://esctoday.com/14627/no_san_marino_either_for_eurovision_2010/|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=4 August 2010|date=2009-12-15}}</ref> The broadcaster announced that it hoped to return to the competition in the future and discussed possible participation in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=6241|title=SMRTV not yet decided on ESC or JESC|last=Konstantopoulos|first=Fotis|date=2009-08-21|publisher=Oikotimes|accessdate=2009-08-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103112907/http://oikotimes.com/v2/index.php?file=articles&id=6241|archivedate=3 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n[[File:ESC2013 - San Marino 03 (crop).jpg|thumb|right|Four time entrant [[Valentina Monetta]] performing in Malm\u00f6 ([[Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]])]]\nAfter a two-year absence from the Contest, San Marino returned in [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]] with Italian singer [[Senit]] performing \"[[Stand By (Senit song)|Stand By]]\", which failed to take the nation to the final. Between 2012 and 2014, San Marino sent [[Valentina Monetta]] to the contest on three consecutive occasions, which made her the first singer to participate in three consecutive contests since [[Udo J\u00fcrgens]], who competed in 1964, 1965 and 1966 for Austria. Her entries in [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]] (\"[[The Social Network Song]]\") and [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]] (\"[[Crisalide (Vola)]]\") also failed to qualify San Marino to the final. However, in [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]], Monetta managed to bring San Marino to the final for the first time, where she placed 24th with the song \"[[Maybe (Valentina Monetta song)|Maybe]]\". In [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]], the nation once again failed to qualify to the final with the song \"[[Chain of Lights]]\" performed by [[Anita Simoncini]] and [[Michele Perniola]]. In [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2016|2016]], San Marino failed to qualify with \"[[I Didn't Know]]\" sung by Turkish performer [[Serhat]]. [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017 |2017]] marked Valentina Monetta's fourth time in the contest, however, her song \"[[Spirit in the Night]]\" (with [[Jimmie Wilson (singer)|Jimmie Wilson]]) placed last in the semi-final, tying San Marino's worst performance. This was only slightly improved upon in 2018 with [[Jessika Muscat|Jessika]] and [[Jenifer Brening]]'s second to last place finish with \"[[Who We Are (Jessika Muscat song)|Who We Are]]\". In [[San Marino in the Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]] San Marino sent Serhat again with the song \"[[Say Na Na Na]] \", finishing in 19th place with 77 points, giving San Marino its best result to date. SMRTV confirmed San Marino's participation at the 2020 Eurovision Song Contest on 25 May 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://escxtra.com/2019/05/25/san-marino-rtv-confirm-2020-participation/|title=San Marino: RTV confirm 2020 participation!|last=Christou|first=Costa|date=25 May 2019|website=escxtra|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Sammarinese national broadcaster, [[San Marino RTV]] (SMRTV), broadcasts the event within San Marino and organises the selection process for the nation's entry. Throughout the years, this selection process has varied from an internal selection, where the broadcaster chooses the entry, to a national final with public input. For 2020, San Marino used a national final-type process titled ''Digital Battle Eurovision''. After selecting the [[Senhit (singer)|Senhit]] internally, an online poll was open for two days from 7 March 2020 until 8 March 2020 in order to select the song she would perform in the 2020 contest. The winning song, \"[[Freaky (Senhit song)|Freaky!]]\" was announced on 9 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/03/06/senhit-san-marino-eurovision-2020-digital-battle/251415/|title=Senhit will represent San Marino at Eurovision 2020 and fans will choose her song in a \u201cdigital battle\u201d|last=Scarpone|first=Cristian|date=6 March 2020|website=Wiwibloggs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Later that month, however, the 2020 Contest was cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019|Coronavirus]] (COVID-19).<ref name=\"cancellation\">{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|title=Eurovision 2020 in Rotterdam is cancelled|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Contestants==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|bgcolor=#FE8080|{{center|\u25c1}}\n|Last place\n|-\n|style=\"background-color:#A4EAA9\"|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete \n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Language\n!Title\n!width=50px|Final\n!width=50px|Points\n!width=50px|Semi\n!widt